actually uses R in many different ways to build our blogs. And so our blogs help keep the community

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:50.079
up to date with events and products. Just to show a few different examples.

00:07:53.119 --> 00:08:00.320
Here is one showcasing the community events, like this one today, and just letting folks know

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:05.279
in terms of what is happening this month, what happened last month, and where to find different

00:08:05.279 --> 00:08:14.559
sorts of resources. Another thing we like to do is showcase what's possible with all the cool

00:08:14.559 --> 00:08:22.079
data science teams and tools that are out there. And so this is an example from the Netherlands

00:08:22.079 --> 00:08:30.000
that actually built a shiny app and scaled it to hundreds of doctors in order to track COVID cases

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:38.239
and make decision-making based on that data and information. And then the other thing is providing

00:08:38.239 --> 00:08:44.159
thought leadership and providing, like I mentioned earlier, opinions about a particular topic.

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:51.919
And so RStudio does put these out as well. So for example, our stance on interoperability between

00:08:51.919 --> 00:08:59.520
Python, between an R, and then also things like the unique ways that code-first data science

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:08.159
can help companies and teams be able to successfully create a data science team.

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:21.119
And so in addition to an external site, you should also consider an internal site or blog for your

00:09:21.119 --> 00:09:26.799
team as well. As this is an R Enterprise community meetup, this is actually the use case we'll be

00:09:26.799 --> 00:09:34.479
mostly focusing on today. And internal blogs can help you share information between team members

00:09:34.479 --> 00:09:39.919
in an easier and more efficient way. I don't know if you've ever tried to find some advice that your

00:09:39.919 --> 00:09:46.559
colleague sent you over email. It can be really hard to find. And with a blog, key information can

00:09:46.559 --> 00:09:52.479
be in one place. It could be searchable with tags. And so this just speeds up communication

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:59.599
since everything's organized within the blog. And serving as a sort of bulletin board of ongoing

00:09:59.599 --> 00:10:06.479
projects in use, folks can search for information from the past while easily seeing what is the

00:10:06.479 --> 00:10:13.119
newest info. And so generally, it gives your colleagues an opportunity to collaborate and

00:10:13.119 --> 00:10:17.760
share their knowledge if they know that there's a place that they can go to when they have something

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:25.760
they want to share. And with a consolidated place like a blog, folks' thoughts can be shared very

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:33.840
quickly to many people rather than siloed in conversations or emails. And others can learn

00:10:33.840 --> 00:10:42.239
about what their teammates are thinking about as well. And so ideally, an internal blog can foster

00:10:42.239 --> 00:10:48.960
a community that's open and inclusive and share the message that you all care about each other's

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:55.119
work and your opinions and your experience. And so there are a few differences between an internal

00:10:55.119 --> 00:11:00.719
blog and an external blog. You don't have to worry about things like keywords or searchability.

00:11:01.599 --> 00:11:08.080
Your audience is confined to those in the organization. So you know exactly how to find

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:13.039
them. And the topics can be a little bit more flexible rather than your company or your products

00:11:13.039 --> 00:11:23.200
like with an official corporate blog. And there are many different types of posts that you can

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:29.599
consider for your blog as well. And this very much depends on your goals, the sort of information that

00:11:29.599 --> 00:11:35.679
your team finds useful. However, let's say you want to create a blog for an internal data science

00:11:35.679 --> 00:11:42.320
community. So topics for your community can include things like reflections on past projects,

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:48.880
how things went, a summary of events, any lessons learned, where to find the outputs, for example.

00:11:50.159 --> 00:11:56.159
You could post things like virtual proposals to get feedback and review. And of course, things

00:11:56.159 --> 00:12:02.640
like news and updates are very well suited to blog posts. But as you can see here, there's many,

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:09.039
many different types that you can consider in terms of how to actually write the information

00:12:09.039 --> 00:12:17.039
that you want to share. And then besides these, there's also the actual content. And blog posts

00:12:17.039 --> 00:12:23.039
are a little bit about finding a sweet spot in terms of length and media, like whether you want

00:12:23.039 --> 00:12:29.599
to fully text the article, images, photos, infographic, videos, podcasts, etc. There's so

00:12:29.599 --> 00:12:35.599
many different ways of actually composing a blog post. And you don't have to worry so much about

00:12:35.599 --> 00:12:43.039
optimization, like I mentioned earlier. But you still want to make sure that your content is

00:12:43.039 --> 00:12:50.080
engaging and useful. And like I mentioned earlier, too, blog posts can serve as a forum for discussion

00:12:50.080 --> 00:12:58.719
if you have comments available on there. But one thing I do want to mention is that a blog is not

00:12:58.719 --> 00:13:04.719
the place for absolutely everything. And so this is a framework that I find very helpful. It's called

00:13:04.719 --> 00:13:13.520
the DITAC-based framework. And it tries to provide structure for technical documentation. So a

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:20.320
successful technical team needs a mix of all of these tutorials, how-tos, explanations, and references.

00:13:21.359 --> 00:13:28.000
And so it's always important to consider, if you have a blog, what is the right place for

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:33.440
a particular type of documentation, whether it should be stored somewhere else in another

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:38.799
location, or if it makes sense to write a blog post about it, and then save it somewhere else

00:13:38.799 --> 00:13:46.000
a little bit more permanently, or write a blog post about something to raise awareness of a

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:53.440
particular resource so it helps people or point people to it for the future. But that is the

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:59.599
one caveat that I want to mention. Not everything is suited for a blog post inside an organization.

00:14:01.760 --> 00:14:08.159
And so in addition, what else do you need to consider if you want to write an internal blog?

00:14:09.599 --> 00:14:14.799
I think first and foremost is why do you want to create an internal blog, and what are your goals

00:14:14.799 --> 00:14:21.919
and your ultimate purpose? Are you hoping to get viewership for just your team or outside of your

00:14:21.919 --> 00:14:27.440
team or others at the organization and hope that they are interested in the work as well?

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:35.440
Are you hoping that the blog stays focused about work projects, or is it more of an opportunity

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:42.080
to learn more about the personal experiences of others? And so having a clear goal can help you

00:14:42.080 --> 00:14:48.320
develop your blog, what it looks like, and help you explain to others its goal and purposes as well.

00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:54.960
And related to your goals, I think it's very important to illustrate the values that you want

00:14:54.960 --> 00:15:04.000
to instill. So if your blog is meant to be a place for inclusivity, openness, a way to motivate your

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:09.359
co-workers, then you want to make sure that the content of your blog demonstrates your values

00:15:09.359 --> 00:15:12.640
and that your colleagues are aware of these values as well.

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:17.440
And another thing to consider is, again, what would be helpful and relevant content?

00:15:18.159 --> 00:15:24.960
What do you want to share that your readers will actually want to read? And for an internal data

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:31.200
science community, what would be interesting enough to check in periodically at your blog to

00:15:31.200 --> 00:15:38.239
learn more for your teammates? A key to success is knowing what others find valuable and making

00:15:38.400 --> 00:15:44.400
A key to success is knowing what others find valuable and making sure that your blog reflects

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:53.520
that information. And like we mentioned before, we don't want a blog to confuse others because

00:15:53.520 --> 00:15:59.919
of the other forms of documentation that already exist within an organization. So it's important

00:15:59.919 --> 00:16:06.640
to know what's in and out of your blog, the tone, style, and voice that it will have,

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:11.599
and what sort of content are within the guardrails of your blog and what is not.

00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:16.239
Of course, as time goes on and you learn things, things may change,

00:16:16.239 --> 00:16:21.440
but having these in place can help you understand how you think you'll meet your goals

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:29.200
and adapt accordingly. And ideally, you can get your colleagues involved in content creation as

00:16:29.200 --> 00:16:34.559
well. This way you can showcase many different voices and perspectives and keep your blog

00:16:34.559 --> 00:16:41.280
updated with diverse ideas. Of course, this means your colleagues must be excited to be

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:46.000
involved and share their own skill sets. And this can be done through direct invitations,

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:51.440
but it is helpful if you have firm values and great content for your blog

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:58.000
to help encourage collaboration. And then another thing to note is that you

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:03.840
want to get buy-in for your blog, not just from your teammates, but also from your leadership team

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:09.439
since it takes time to create content. You might have to make the case that it's worth the time and

00:17:09.439 --> 00:17:16.000
effort of not just you, but also your colleagues to keep a frequently updated blog. And this is

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:21.359
done through the creation of valuable content, work that makes it interesting and useful and

00:17:21.359 --> 00:17:27.839
applicable to others, and being able to communicate the value of that work to higher-ups.

00:17:27.839 --> 00:17:32.800
And with inviting folks to collaborate, you want to make sure that your blog reflects your values.

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:48.880
And so, like, if your blog's values are to be inclusive, you don't want to unintentionally

00:17:49.439 --> 00:17:54.479
exclude folks with the topics or the way that folks respond to discussions.

00:17:54.800 --> 00:18:01.280
So, getting consistent feedback and help can help determine whether your blog

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:05.359
is truly benefiting your team and reflecting the values that you want to put in place.

00:18:07.280 --> 00:18:13.439
And related to ownership, you want the blog to be a part of the routine of your work so that it

00:18:13.439 --> 00:18:20.479
doesn't feel like a big imposition or burden on you or others. Perhaps your co-workers have given

00:18:21.280 --> 00:18:28.000
a conference talk, or you just had a big strategy meeting. Can a blog post just be part of the workflow

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:34.400
so that the blog has regular content, but it's not a creation of a whole new thing?

00:18:35.040 --> 00:18:41.439
And if it's already somewhat integrated, then it's a lot easier to keep the blog going.

00:18:41.439 --> 00:18:49.040
And then, finally, there is the technical stuff, too. So, there's the actual tools that you'll be

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:55.439
using to build your blog, and the training around those tools. You don't want something like a blog

00:18:55.439 --> 00:19:00.239
to disappear when a particular person, you know, moves to another team or something like that.

00:19:01.439 --> 00:19:07.439
And hopefully, you can build the skills across your team to make sure that your blog doesn't

00:19:07.439 --> 00:19:11.280
disappear. And hopefully, you can build the skills across your team,

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:14.959
the infrastructure across your organization to keep it going.

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:26.479
And so, to build a blog with R specifically, at least for the tools that I will mention today,

00:19:26.479 --> 00:19:33.680
you'll have to have some skills like R and R Markdown, and make sure that it's not just one

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:39.040
person, but multiple people that have those skills in place, or at least a workflow to help

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:46.000
those who are still learning R and R Markdown so that they are also able to contribute to the blog

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:54.560
if they want to. And while you don't need a system like GitHub, it's incredibly helpful to have.

00:19:55.680 --> 00:20:01.839
Version control can help resolve issues like a particular conflict if two people edit the same

00:20:01.839 --> 00:20:08.079
file at the same time or something like that. And it can help keep track of changes. And then

00:20:08.079 --> 00:20:13.119
when they happen, being able to revert it and things like that. So, highly recommend having

00:20:13.119 --> 00:20:20.000
version control in place. And then, of course, you need a place to actually host your website.

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:26.880
And there are a few different options for if you're looking for a personal website,

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:30.880
which we'll go through today. If you're looking for a blog for your internal

00:20:32.479 --> 00:20:38.079
company, then you will need to take other considerations into place, like if you want

00:20:38.079 --> 00:20:45.520
it behind your server so that it's secure, or behind a password, or on other protected

00:20:45.520 --> 00:20:51.920
hosting services like Netlify or RStudio Connect, which, again, we'll go through later.

